    selectCount: 3,
    rationale: "Daily cannabis use (A) is associated with increased anesthetic requirements due to cross-tolerance with sedative-hypnotics, and chronic use can cause cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome. Chronic benzodiazepine use (C) causes cross-tolerance with GABA-A agonists (propofol, barbiturates, volatile agents), significantly increasing induction and maintenance drug requirements. Active cocaine use (D) causes catecholamine excess, coronary vasospasm, and dangerous hemodynamic instability under anesthesia; it also depletes norepinephrine stores. Caffeine (B) does not significantly affect anesthetic pharmacology. Occasional acetaminophen use (E) at standard doses does not affect anesthetic drug selection.",
