    selectCount: 2,
    rationale: "The HPI is a detailed narrative that characterizes the chief complaint using frameworks like OPQRST, while the ROS is a separate, systematic head-to-toe yes/no symptom screen (A). Pertinent negatives from the ROS \u2014 symptoms the patient denies \u2014 are clinically valuable because they help exclude diagnoses from the differential (C). For example, denying fever and night sweats in a patient with weight loss makes infectious or malignant etiologies less likely. The ROS does not replace the HPI under any circumstances (B). The ROS is completed after the HPI, not before \u2014 the HPI establishes the clinical context that guides which ROS domains to emphasize (D).",
